summarys.summary: Hello (stylized as HELLO!) is a weekly magazine specializing in celebrity news and human-interest stories, published in the United Kingdom since 1988. Hello is sister magazine to ¡Hola!, the Spanish weekly magazine launched in Spain in 1944. ¡HOLA! Spanish, Hello UK, and ¡HOLA! Mexican – launched in 2006 – make up the magazines published by HOLA, S.A and distributed in over 100 countries. Local editions of the magazine are also published in Argentina, Bulgaria, Canada, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Ecuador, Greece, India, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Middle East, Morocco, Nigeria, Pakistan, Peru, Puerto Rico, Russia, Serbia, Thailand, Turkey and Venezuela.

pastExamSents.en: I wanted to say hello to him but I forgot his name.
pastExamSents.zh: 我想跟他打个招呼，但忘记了他的名字。

pastExamSents.en: They're watched by millions, but I still find it strange when people I don't know say hello to me in the street.
pastExamSents.zh: 成千上万的人都在看它们，但当我不认识的人在街上跟我打招呼的时候，我还是觉得很奇怪。

pastExamSents.en: In Teahouse, the writer Lao She says goodbye to the old Chinese society and hello to the new one.
pastExamSents.zh: 在《茶馆》中，作家老舍告别中国旧社会，迎接了新社会。

pastExamSents.en: Sometimes we see some strangers so many times that we know their faces well, but we never even say hello to them.
pastExamSents.zh: 有时我们见到一些陌生人太多次，所以我们很熟悉他们的脸，但我们甚至从来没有跟他们打招呼。

pastExamSents.en: She was scared to say hello to strangers.
pastExamSents.zh: 她害怕和陌生人打招呼。

pastExamSents.en: Myra wondered if she should say hello.
pastExamSents.zh: 迈拉不知道该不该打个招呼。

pastExamSents.en: "Hello," he said in a confident voice.
pastExamSents.zh: “你好。”他自信地说。

pastExamSents.en: Let's go and say hello to her.
pastExamSents.zh: 我们去跟她打个招呼吧。

pastExamSents.en: Later that day, Zhang replied to Curry, "Hello, Curry!"
pastExamSents.zh: 当天晚些时候，张回复库里：“你好，库里！”

pastExamSents.en: Hello, may I speak to Gina?
pastExamSents.zh: 你好，我可以和吉娜说句话吗？

pastExamSents.en: No one forgets to say hello to the parents when they return from school.
pastExamSents.zh: 他们从学校回来时，都不会忘记向父母问好。

pastExamSents.en: Let's say hello to him.
pastExamSents.zh: 我们去向他问好吧。

pastExamSents.en: "Hello," I replied, not looking at him.
pastExamSents.zh: “你好。”我并没有看他，回答道。

pastExamSents.en: I also bought a Hello Doggy hair band.
pastExamSents.zh: 我还买了一个 Hello Doggy 发带。

pastExamSents.en: Do you need a hairband?
pastExamSents.zh: 您需要发带吗？

pastExamSents.en: Mina waved to Nate, who waved back, and called hello to her teacher.
pastExamSents.zh: 米娜向内特挥手，内特也向她招手，并和她的老师打招呼。

pastExamSents.en: An alarm clock, called Hello Sense, can improve your sleep.
pastExamSents.zh: 一个叫做 “Hello Sense” 的闹钟可以改善你的睡眠。

pastExamSents.en: Do what you think might help others feel good, for example, say hello or smile.
pastExamSents.zh: 做你认为可以帮助他人感觉良好的事情，例如，打招呼或微笑。

pastExamSents.en: Hello and welcome to "Words and Their Stories".
pastExamSents.zh: 大家好，欢迎收听“词汇掌故”节目。

pastExamSents.en: Sometimes we share a friendly smile or say hello, but lots of people don't even know their neighbor's names! When you don't know someone, it's easy to be angry when something has happened that you think is unfair.
pastExamSents.zh: 有时我们会给彼此一个友好的微笑或打招呼，但很多人甚至不知道他们的邻居的名字！当你不认识某人时，在你认为不公平的事情发生时生气。

sents.sentOrig: Honestly, if we got stuck in the rut of “hi”, “hello”, “how are you?” and “what's going on?” you will fail to give the initial jolt to the conversation that's can make it so memorable.
sents.sentSpeech: Honestly, if we got stuck in the rut of “hi”, “hello”, “how are you?” and “what's going on?” you will fail to give the initial jolt to the conversation that's can make it so memorable.
sents.sentTrans: 老实说，如果我们过度使用“嗨”，“你好”，“你好吗？”和“最近还好吗？”这些问候语，你将无法给谈话带来最初的激情，也就无法让谈话变得令人难忘。
